ole><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FH03918X%2F1"><gtr:id>C7AB794C-F111-444A-9B7A-52A7045851F3</gtr:id><gtr:title>Council housing, slum clearance and the modernization of working class neighbourhoods in contemporary Britain</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/H03918X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>During the middle years of the twentieth century (c.1925-1975) the most important changes in working class people's lives resulted from the reconfiguration of the built environment through slum clearance and suburbanisation. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research will highlight the extent to which neighbourhoods were re-made from without (by slum clearance, council house allocations and sales) and from within via the mobility individuals and families. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Council housing meant more space and privacy both within and between households, a process underpinned by a decline in average family size. Improvements in housing and amenities combined with circumscribed opportunities for everyday sociability to encourage a partial reorientation from the street to the home as the locus of social life. Nevertheless there were continuities between the older neighbourhoods and the council estates in terms of kinship networks and neighbouring practices. There were continuities too in terms of the ways in which particular working class neighbourhoods were stigmatised as 'slums'. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Using life history methodologies and analytical frameworks drawn from sociology, cultural theory and social history, this project will explore the extent to which classed experiences of home and neighbourhood intersected with those of work and family to produce social identities and collective memories.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2010-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>72408</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>0C3DCD03-C3B4-48F8-97E1-56C6B7A7DC64</gtr:id><gtr:title>Slum clearance, privatization and residualization: the practices and politics of council housing in mid-twentieth-century England.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>20 century British history</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/02a692102c18c95a1f2217f9c024bb0c"><gtr:id>02a692102c18c95a1f2217f9c024bb0c</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Jones B</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0955-2359</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>pm_53cbfe0bfe0f70cc9</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>766368BF-59AA-4F45-B37F-7C14155F26AA</gtr:id><gtr:title>The limits to nostalgia : slum clearance and social memory in post-war England</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr